# Defining the map function
def dummies(x,df):
    temp = pd.get_dummies(df[x], drop_first = True)
    #, drop_first = True
    df = pd.concat([df, temp], axis = 1)
    df.drop([x], axis = 1, inplace = True)
    return df
# Applying the function to the cars_lr

geely = dummies('carbody',geely)
geely = dummies('drivewheel',geely)
geely = dummies('enginetype',geely)
geely = dummies('cylindernumber',geely)
geely = dummies('CarName',geely)
geely = dummies('fuelsystem',geely)

# Check for the VIF values of the feature variables. 
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Create a dataframe that will contain the names of all the feature variables and their respective VIFs
vif = pd.DataFrame()
X_train = X_train_lm
vif['Features'] = X_train.columns
vif['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(X_train.values, i) for i in range(X_train.shape[1])]
vif['VIF'] = round(vif['VIF'], 2)
vif = vif.sort_values(by = "VIF", ascending = True)

conclusions 

1) the error distribution is normal
2) r2 , adjusted r2 is quite similar and f-tastic probablity is almost 0 which means the model and its fit are well explained
3) Some parameters have been retained eg symboling , and redundant size and engine parameters since they make business sense
4) these parameters have a lower probablity but can swing with a few changes like attractive insurance
5) car width and length etc have high VIF but again are decisive parameters for a consumer
6) Similarly engine parameters like stroke are related but will generaly be part of custmer decisions and will affect pricing
7) r2_score(y_test, y_pred) = 0.873207703150322
8) luxury cars like porsche bmw have a better pricing as expected
